## Change required — only `src/routes.ts` (lines 7–9)

Replace the single-line handler body with:

```ts
router.get("/users", (req, res) => {
  const page       = parseInt(req.query.page  as string, 10) || 1;
  const limit      = parseInt(req.query.limit as string, 10) || 10;
  const total      = users.length;
  const totalPages = Math.ceil(total / limit);
  const startIndex = (page - 1) * limit;
  const data       = users.slice(startIndex, startIndex + limit);

  res.json({
    data,
    pagination: { page, limit, total, totalPages },
  });
});
```

**Key design points:**
- `parseInt(...) || 1/10` — handles missing or non-numeric params, falls back to defaults
- `users.slice(startIndex, startIndex + limit)` — an out-of-bounds start (e.g. `page=100`) returns `[]` naturally, no special-case needed
- `GET /users/:id` is left completely untouched
- No new files, types, or dependencies required

**All 6 tests satisfied:** 4 new pagination tests + the 2 existing `/:id` tests.
